player.seasonOutlook: Widely regarded the best player in baseball, Trout is no longer a slam dunk for the same honor in fantasy baseball. He placed outside the top 25 on the Player Rater while posting the worst full-season batting average (.281) and second-worst contact rate (71.9%) of his career in 2020, and he has missed 105 Angels games (most due to injuries) since the beginning of 2017. Still, that Trout's No. 27 Player Rater finish represented his lowest in any of his nine full big-league seasons speaks volumes about his Hall of Fame caliber skill set. Just since the beginning of 2018, his 101 home runs lead the majors, 252 runs scored rank sixth, .298 batting average and 229 RBI each rank 14th and 36 stolen bases rank 21st. It's the latter category that sparks genuine worry, as Trout attempted only two steals in 53 games in 2020, and as a 29-year-old, that's a skill unlikely to significantly rebound. His power metrics look as strong as ever, and with good luck in the health department that he should remain one of the most valuable commodities in fantasy. But with that No. 1 overall pick, it's probably wiser to go with someone younger or who steals more bases.

Nobody expected Ryu to replicate his second-place Cy Young finish from 2019 in his age-33 season last year, but he came pretty darn close, finishing third in the voting on the back of a 2.69 ERA. His walk rate in his first year with the Blue Jays may have nearly doubled from 3.3% to 6.2%, but that came with a jump in strikeout rate from 22.5% to 26.2%. He also produced a career-best 51.1% groundball rate. The lefty did lose a tick on his fastball, which came in at 89.6 mph on average, but he adjusted by using it just 34.7% of the time, increasing his cutter usage to compensate. Ryu will be 34 by Opening Day, and he's near the lower limit of velocity for an elite pitcher, but he's been strong all-around and healthy for several seasons now.
